The solution approach relies on the key insight that the internal tangent line intersects the line connecting the centers of the circles at a point that divides the line into parts proportional to the radii of the circles. By identifying this point of intersection and using the proportionality of the divided parts, we can determine the lengths of the line segments forming the internal tangent line and thus find the shortest distance between the tangent points on the circles.
The centers are at $A=(10,0)$ and $B=(-15,0)$, and the radii are 6 and 9, respectively. Since the internal tangent is shorter than the external tangent, $\overline{PQ}$ intersects  $\overline{AB}$ at a point $D$ that divides  $\overline{AB}$ into parts proportional to the radii. The right triangles $\triangle APD$ and $\triangle BQD$ are similar with ratio of similarity $2:3$. Therefore, $D=(0,0), \, PD=8,$ and $QD=12$. Thus $PQ=\boxed{20}$.

